  "doc_id": "58279",
  "text": "Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT) results from an atypical immune response to platelet factor 4/heparin complexes (PF4/H), with rapid synthesis of platelet-activating IgG antibodies that activate platelets via FcγRIIA receptors [CITATION_1] . The risk of HIT is probably dependent on the intensity of this immune response, since the likelihood of developing thrombocytopenia and thrombotic complications has been related to the plasma levels of IgG antibodies to PF4 [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . However, the reasons explaining why only a subset of patients treated with heparin and who develop significant levels of IgG to PF4/H complexes will present with HIT remain to be fully defined.",
